onfidential counselling and testing (VCCT) centres, and support services for PLHIV all require substantial financial and political commitment from governments. UNAIDS has attempted to measure the degree of investment priority that governments have given", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "198011b0-6ec5-4e72-bd73-fede6a5946d8": {"__data__": {"id_": "198011b0-6ec5-4e72-bd73-fede6a5946d8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-level-asia-regional-analysis-impact-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Socio-Economic Impact of HIV at the Household Level in Asia: A Regional Analysis of the Impact on Women and Girls", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-level-asia-regional-analysis-impact-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0273b17c694563356625253b14c937bda15038d67618d2988c32906ce6c13861"}, "3": {"node_id": "463f8d4b-9eae-4eaa-bc9d-aff387ea25a9", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-level-asia-regional-analysis-impact-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "56619471e0e98aceac73d0ab6014ae1d3e3a38f4c5894520ec487f9016112f7e"}}, "hash": "6d41576b1c4e6e9f8a8f94ac955de7a43971148bb8724ba7b0d69fca04d79c4a", "text": "to support their national AIDS responses through the \u201cDomestic Investment Priority Index\u201d (DIPI) (UNAIDS, 2010). It is calculated by dividing the percentage of government revenue directed to the AIDS response by the country\u2019s HIV prevalence: 1 Sub-Saharan Africa is the highest in all three counts. 2 Key populations = \u201ckey populations at higher risk of HIV exposure\u201d (UNAIDS, 2011) Chapter Summary The report is an analysis of five socio-economic impact studies in Asia: Cambodia, China, India, Indonesia and Viet Nam; The report systematically address information gaps regarding the socio-economic impacts of HIV on women and girls in the region; In Cambodia, China, India and Viet Nam, the HIV epidemic is concentrated and prevalances have either remained steady or decreased in recent years. However, in Indonesia, prevalence has increased, and certain parts of the country are experiencing a generalized epidemic. The report focuses on impacts on employment; coping mechanisms such as debt, asset liquidation and migration; educational impacts; health utilisation; knowledge and awareness regarding HIV; food security; stigma and discrimination; pregnancy; intimate partner transmission; widowhood; and policy recommendations. 5 Introduction Public expenditure on AIDS response Government revenue DIPI = \u00d7 National population PLHIV A higher DIPI figure usually means a higher priority, with the global mean value of 0.35. A comparison of their DIPI and other basic indicators for the included countries is shown above in Table 1. The percentage of PLHIV who are women, ranges from a high of 56% in Cambodia (35,000 of 63,000 PLHIV) to a low of 28% in Indonesia (88,000 of 310,000 PLHIV). The table also displays that the percentage of PLHIV receiving ART generally mirrors the percentage of female PLHIV, from a high of 52% in Cambodia to a low of 25% in Indonesia. The size of the countries varies from the two largest in the world - China and India - with over a billion people each, to Cambodia with less than 15 million people. The smallest of the countries is also the poorest - Cambodia is considered a low-income country by the World Bank, while the others are considered lower middle- income countries. The prevalence ranges, low overall, range from a high of 0.5% in Cambodia to a low of 0.1% in China. However, due to China and India\u2019s large populations, the estimated number of PLHIV is still very high in those countries \u2013 almost 2.5 million in India and 750,000 in China. As discussed earlier, the ART coverage rates in the countries, also varies significantly, from the high of 94% in Cambodia, to a low of 21% in Indonesia, using the WHO 2010 guidelines. Finally, the level of VCCT centres throughout the countries ranges from a high of 2.9 / 100,000 population in Cambodia to a low of 0.2 in Viet Nam. The percentage of pregnant women who received an HIV test in East, South and South East Asia increased from 2% in 2005 to 17% in 2009, but is still much lower than the 26% 2009 global average for low and middle-income countries (WHO, 2010). 1.3 Overview of HIV and Women in Cambodia More than 35,000 women are currently living with HIV in Cambodia. While national HIV prevalence is relatively low (calculated at 0.9% in 2006 and estimated at 0.5% in 2011 by UNAIDS), prevalence is still unacceptably high in certain female sub-populations, such as female sex workers (14.7% in 2006) and indirect female sex workers (9.4% in 2006) (NCHADS, 2007; NAA, 2010). Heterosexual transmission outside of brothels continues to be a problem, and while the actual number of women living with HIV is decreasing, women comprise an increasing proportion of all people living with HIV. In 1997, only 37% of all people living with HIV were women. However, the Asian Epidemic Model projects that, by 2012, 52% of all people living with HIV in Cambodia will be women. Conversely, by 2012, it is projected that women will only account for 43% of new infections, down from 53% in 2006. HIV infection among women has serious consequences for child health.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "463f8d4b-9eae-4eaa-bc9d-aff387ea25a9": {"__data__": {"id_": "463f8d4b-9eae-4eaa-bc9d-aff387ea25a9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-level-asia-regional-analysis-impact-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Socio-Economic Impact of HIV at the Household Level in Asia: A Regional Analysis of the Impact on Women and Girls", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-level-asia-regional-analysis-impact-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0273b17c694563356625253b14c937bda15038d67618d2988c32906ce6c13861"}, "2": {"node_id": "198011b0-6ec5-4e72-bd73-fede6a5946d8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-level-asia-regional-analysis-impact-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6d41576b1c4e6e9f8a8f94ac955de7a43971148bb8724ba7b0d69fca04d79c4a"}}, "hash": "56619471e0e98aceac73d0ab6014ae1d3e3a38f4c5894520ec487f9016112f7e", "text": "HIV infection among women has serious consequences for child health. The prevention of Mother-To-Child-Transmission (PMTCT) program tested 18.8% of pregnant women and provided prophylaxis for 10.7% of exposed neonates (UNAIDS 2008). As of 2009, 32.3% of HIV positive women received ART to prevent mother-to-child-transmission. Despite these efforts, concern still exists regarding the number of new infections among newborns (UNAIDS 2008). While access to treatment has improved, Cambodia still faces challenges in relation to the promotion of VCCT. Despite an increase in the number of testing centres (from 12 in 2001 to 233 in 2009, or 2.9 centres / 100,000 population), levels of voluntary counselling and test are still low.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "45d4af79-5ffa-4a17-9eb5-1c392318770b": {"__data__": {"id_": "45d4af79-5ffa-4a17-9eb5-1c392318770b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-level-asia-regional-analysis-impact-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Socio-Economic Impact of HIV at the Household Level in Asia: A Regional Analysis of the Impact on Women and Girls", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-level-asia-regional-analysis-impact-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e2de57fa8fa37f9b702b13d1118cc2c6c47db4db876894f9d95a76cd8ecd43d4"}, "3": {"node_id": "29aef690-e0fc-4fa1-8861-2f9fc5677765", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-level-asia-regional-analysis-impact-women-and-girls", "Author": "United Nations Development Prog