f the reports indicated they were displaying Workforce Participation Rates, but due to lack of detailed methodology descriptions, it was unclear that strict WFPRs had been created. As such, the term employment is used throughout this section. China: WFPR for members 15-59. India: WFPR for members 15-60. Data was not available for NA-HHs by sex. Indonesia: Alive HH-members between the ages of 15-60. Viet Nam: Alive HH-members between the ages of 15-60 in an income-earning position (housewives and peer educators excluded). Figure 7 shows unemployment levels for PLHIV, non-PLHIV members of HIV-HHs and members of NA-HHs (the percentage of 15 to 60 year olds not working, performing housework or attending school), by sex. Across all countries, unemployment levels are substantially higher for PLHIV than non-PLHIV. However, additional impacts on the employment of HIV-HH members are also seen, with non-PLHIV members of HIV-HHs in China and Indonesia having substantially higher unemployment rates than members of NA-HHs (those in Cambodia and Viet Nam showed only small increases in unemployment rates). This impact is likely due to the need for caregiving by household members, as discussed in the following section. The figure also highlights the additional gender impacts of HIV. While in Cambodia male and female PLHIV have similar unemployment levels, females in Indonesia and Viet Nam were less likely to be unemployed, pointing to their need to continue to work regardless of their health status. The same situation was true for India (which only had sex-segregated data for PLHIV), where 14% of male PLHIV versus 5% of female PLHIV reported being unemployed.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "124ccbe7-c469-4b24-b67b-d52406f23e28": {"__data__": {"id_": "124ccbe7-c469-4b24-b67b-d52406f23e28", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": 